  "doc_id": "31639",
  "text": "In a cohort of 103 patients presenting to hospital within three hours of haemorrhagic stroke, 38% of patients had more than 33% growth in haematoma volume. [CITATION_1] Another study found that in a cohort of 25 patients presenting within 4.5 hours of a haemorrhagic stroke, 10 patients had haematoma expansion of more than 12.5 mL during the first six hours in hospital. [CITATION_2] Although it is appealing to visualise haematoma expansion as being caused by a continuous bleed from a single vessel, it is more likely that expansion of the haemorrhage causes shearing and rupture of neighbouring vessels as a sort of avalanche effect. 13 14 ",
